Be Shaka Zulu of the Zulus, and instead of desperately fending off the  Dutch, you build beautiful, large cities and make incredible works of art - or be Catherine of Russia, building a ing spaceship that will take you to", "Sid Meier's Alpha Centauri", 'in lieu of abusing a horse\'s innate lack of agency. Really, you can even be Ramkhamhaeng, and instead of not existing, you can be a total ing  to your friends by exploiting your overpowered-as- Uinique Ability and taking as many City-State allies as possible. The  you can do in this game is practically limitless (not really, though). There are several ways to win, but given the pretty linear design of the tech tree, you will begin to develop winning patterns once you begin playing (assuming you haven\'t played any of Civ V\'s predecessors). Like the total ing scrublord you are, you will groan angrily and ragequit the moment you see a large army at your doorstep (stop turtling like a , ), or you\'ll break your keyboard and start sending Anthrax-laced letters to Cairo, Egypt, after seeing that Ramsses built the Great Library before you (turn on production tiles or stop using the GL as a crutch, dumbo). Really, if Ramsses and his whole, "My name is Ozymandias, honkey, / Gaze upon my great works, , and cry home to mommy," keeps stealin\' wonders from you, you know what you do? You take them from him. That\'s right, it\'s not even hard to do, because (legitimate complaint here) the AI is total  at it, even at higher difficulties. It\'s like playing chess with my asthmatic eight-year-old step-brother; they make a metric -ton of mistakes and still talk  at you, acting as if', "you're", "the one who is mentally incapable of telling a guy to go shoot someone. Why do these great leaders suck so much balls at war when half of them are famous for being warmongering jackasses? Is it bad AI? Is it aliens? Is it the Democrats? We'll never truly know (it's bad AI). Speaking of bad AI, this is made up for in higher difficulties by giving the AI a ton of things for free. On Immortal and Deity, they start off with an extra settler, workers, and a ton of techs that you actually have to work for. This is a huge in' design flaw, as rather than actually giving the player a smarter opponent to deal with, it basically gives everyone other than yourself handicaps. Either way,", 'Civilization V', "still manages to be fun, drawing you in for gobs of hours at a time. It's an excellent work, and will always demand of you just one more turn. This in' game has stolen more than ten days of my life, and still, I come back. I think that line in itself is testament to how well-designed Sid's fifth Civ baby is. To conclude this review, Civ V: Complete Edition is well worth the, like, seventy or so dollars I think it is. I don't know why I wrote this."]

Rest of the review's contents: ['Recommended', '582.6 hrs on record', 'Posted: June 26, 2014', "A few years back, I seem to remember seeing one of the older Civilization games at Target. I picked it up, took it home, played for a couple hours and then hated it. Apparently that version of me was an idiot. I don't know what it was last summer, a couple months before Brave New World came out. But I saw this game and for some reason decided to get the demo. I played the demo. And then I played it again. And again. It was around the sixth time that I realized I should probably buy the game. Fast forward a year later and this is still one of my favorite Steam purchases. I don't know what to say that hasn't already been said about the game. If you're into strategy games then this is quite the blast. There's a lot of fun even in simply experiementing with each civilization's perks against AI and other players. Admittedly, the multiplayer seems to propped up on fragile legs (at least in my experience), but we're usually determined enough to plod through these issues for any given game. The Workshop community is fantastic. There's a lot of cool stuff out there that changes quite the variety of different aspects, from simple UI adjustments or infomration access changes to entirely new game modes. The work that goes into these is really impressive. If you're up in the air, download the demo and give it a go. But this game gets my stamp of approval."]
